{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"96771239-f4d7-4e70-90b3-0d4570e5ffe0","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Microsoft identity platform | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Windows | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with JWT bearer auth (Individual)\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n\n# Azure AD / Entra ID auth\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com -o MyApi\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` to see all options including `--use-controllers`, `--use-minimal-apis`, and framework version flags.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48a27826-0be8-46a4-bb25-4191ec4e01d6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":271,"requestId":"4046:1F3FEB:E7F4D2A:10104F9A:69EC0DED"},"id":"812e8182-4df5-4068-92b2-5321c1823420","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:42:29.154Z","parentId":"b03340d2-d67e-4fd0-897e-7693336a59e3"}
